# Actuarial Model Parity Rules

All work in this repo must maintain exact parity between the Python calculation engine
and the generated Excel workbook. See `docs/model_parity_contract.md` for the full contract.

## Before declaring any task "done"

1. Run `pytest tests/parity/ -v` — all parity tests must pass (0.00 discrepancy).
2. Run `pytest tests/ -v` — all unit tests must pass.
3. If you changed any formula-generating code, regenerate the workbook and verify the
   reconciliation sheet shows 0.00 difference between Python and Excel outputs.

## Critical invariants — never break these

- **Tie-break policy**: When buckets/items have equal or near-equal sort keys, the
  lower-indexed item is always processed first. Use `index * epsilon` tie-breaking in both
  Python and Excel. See `docs/model_parity_contract.md` for exact epsilon and threshold values.
- **Tolerance policy**: Use only the tolerances defined in the parity contract. Never add
  ad-hoc tolerances without updating the contract and adding a regression test.
- **Epsilon policy**: Any change to epsilon or comparison threshold requires a regression
  test proving no double-trigger behavior across all golden scenarios.
- **Step-level parity**: Validate intermediate state (monthly or step-level), not only
  the final output. Matching final values can mask offsetting errors.

## Floating-point accumulation — known failure mode

Values computed by repeated addition/subtraction WILL diverge from values that were reset
to an exact reference value, even when both should represent the same quantity. The error
is typically ~1e-16 but CAN flip comparison order. Always use epsilon tie-breaking;
never rely on raw floating-point comparison for ordering.

## When changing disinvestment / selection logic

- Add a test in `tests/parity/` that covers the new edge case.
- Simulate the Excel formula logic in Python (see `tests/parity/excel_formula_sim.py`)
  and assert agreement at every step.
- Every bug gets a `@pytest.mark.regression` test with the exact scenario.
